Why Jerome Powell must go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden is faced with a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – thus to possibly the most powerful position within the world economy?
A wrong decision here can have far-reaching consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to adequately regulate the banking system, thereby laying the groundwork for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the reaction of the political decision-makers to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and nurtured a lasting sense of discontent among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a multitude of clichés as to why Jerome Powell, the current Federal Reserve Chairman, should be reconfirmed in office.
It would be a demonstration of bipartisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience would be needed to lead us through the recovery in the wake of the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I had heard 25 years ago when I was chairman of the economic advisory board of US President Bill Clinton and Greenspan's reconfirmation was at issue.
They were sufficient to convince Clinton, and the country has dearly paid for his decision.
Interestingly, President Ronald Reagan paid little heed to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied Volcker a second term after he had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed a lot to Volcker, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an Ayn Rand admirer.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity to conflicting objectives are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
Can we be confident that markets are efficient, stable, fair, and driven by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US have consistently held distinct, but clearly articulated views on these issues (at least until the Republicans succumbed to populist delusions).
From my perspective, Democrats are right to be concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis has shown that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
We know that traditionally, only during times of tight labor markets, marginalized groups are brought into the economy and wage disparities are reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a trial by fire for every US Federal Reserve Chairman.
The US is already facing difficult decisions on how to address inflation.
Are the recent price hikes essentially minor issues stemming from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, which has yet to return to its pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and thereby an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: while mispricing with mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of an even more pervasive and widespread mispricing of assets linked to climate change.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Jerome Powell is not the right man for the job.
Initially, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump, thus risking the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding climate risk, although other central bankers worldwide have already declared it the central problem of the coming decades.
Jerome Powell would argue that climate issues are outside the Fed's mandate, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is exactly what the economy does not need right now.
A glaring lack of competition and the absence of sufficient regulation already allow for excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell with the Fed's response to the pandemic.
But every second-year student would have known that during a recession you can't tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as MIT's Simon Johnson has argued, Powell does not feel particularly committed to full employment.
On the contrary, Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve was marked by a series of misjudgments on monetary policy tightening, dating back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the central bank's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policy has significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as premature interest rate hikes can strangle growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the latest scandal over stock trading by senior Fed officials has eroded confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of conflict of interest issues, including those involving the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been a concern of mine for a long time.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in US institutions, there is now a genuine risk that confidence in the integrity of the central bank will further erode.
No Fed official should need an ethics advisor to decide when certain stock trades appear unseemly.
The Fed bears a certain resemblance to the US Supreme Court.
This should be above politics, yet we know since Bush v. Gore that this is not the case.
He has made it clear for all those who still had doubts.
Also, the Fed is supposed to be independent, yet Powell and Greenspan, by following the deregulation agenda of their party, have clearly demonstrated that this is also not the case.
However, while the Federal Reserve Board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, traditionally the power has been concentrated in the hands of the Federal Reserve Chairman - much more so than in the hands of the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the Federal Reserve Chairman who decides what comes to a vote and which issues are put on the backburner or given priority.
The climate issue is just one example where it's crucial who is at the helm of the Fed.
The US needs a central bank that truly commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Whoever believes we can rely on unbridled markets or that regulation is already too extensive lacks vision.
We need neither an ideologue like Greenspan nor a lawyer sympathetic to Wall Street like Powell.
Someone with a deep understanding of macroeconomics is needed, and one who shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are undoubtedly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden doesn't have to look far to find someone who has already demonstrated their capabilities.
Lael Brainard already sits on the central bank board, where she has demonstrated her competence and won the confidence of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank leader who maintains continuity and does not disrupt the markets, but who shares his economic and social program.
